00:00:04,400 --> 00:00:07,870
PROFESSOR: Today we begin the
third major part of the class.

3
00:00:07,870 --> 00:00:10,630
We've done paper
folding, linkage folding,

4
00:00:10,630 --> 00:00:12,880
and now we're going to
do polyhedron folding.

5
00:00:12,880 --> 00:00:25,360

6
00:00:25,360 --> 00:00:27,720
The very last topic we
did was hinged dissection,

7
00:00:27,720 --> 00:00:30,684
which is somewhere in the
middle of all these things.

8
00:00:30,684 --> 00:00:32,100
But with polyhedron
folding, we're

9
00:00:32,100 --> 00:00:34,150
thinking about a two
dimensional surface

10
00:00:34,150 --> 00:00:40,260
in 3D, something like
a cube, and we're

11
00:00:40,260 --> 00:00:50,790
interested in cutting along
the edges of that shape

12
00:00:50,790 --> 00:00:54,970
or somehow cutting along
the surface-- that's

13
00:00:54,970 --> 00:01:02,990
a good cutting-- and then
unfolding into some flat shape.

14
00:01:02,990 --> 00:01:10,270

15
00:01:10,270 --> 00:01:13,420
So this is a standard cross
unfolding of the cube.

16
00:01:13,420 --> 00:01:17,810
This is the unfolding process,
and of course the reverse

17
00:01:17,810 --> 00:01:24,590
is the folding process, and
both of them are interesting.

18
00:01:24,590 --> 00:01:26,850
We're going to start
thinking about unfolding.

19
00:01:26,850 --> 00:01:29,690
That's one of the most
practical problems here.

20
00:01:29,690 --> 00:01:35,360
You really want to build some
3D shape out of sheet material.

21
00:01:35,360 --> 00:01:37,430
What shape do you
cut out in order

22
00:01:37,430 --> 00:01:40,801
to bend it into that surface?

23
00:01:40,801 --> 00:01:42,050
So you start with the surface.

24
00:01:42,050 --> 00:01:45,610
You need to figure out where
to cut so that when you unfold,

25
00:01:45,610 --> 00:01:47,787
you get something
that has no overlap.

26
00:01:47,787 --> 00:01:49,370
If you want to make
it from one sheet,

27
00:01:49,370 --> 00:01:52,910
it shouldn't have any overlap,
and ideally just one piece

28
00:01:52,910 --> 00:01:56,470
because then you have to do
less welding or edge joining

29
00:01:56,470 --> 00:02:00,730
to make that surface.

30
00:02:00,730 --> 00:02:02,496
So today and the
next couple lectures

31
00:02:02,496 --> 00:02:04,620
will be all about unfolding,
and then eventually we

32
00:02:04,620 --> 00:02:08,880
will turn to the reverse
problem, folding problem.

33
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:11,940
And there are two
kinds of unfolding.

34
00:02:11,940 --> 00:02:14,980
The one that I just
drew is an edge

35
00:02:14,980 --> 00:02:19,510
unfolding because it
only cuts along edges.

36
00:02:19,510 --> 00:02:33,470
Edge unfolding only cut
along edges of the surface.

37
00:02:33,470 --> 00:02:34,510
This property is nice.

38
00:02:34,510 --> 00:02:36,580
If you're building
something, you

39
00:02:36,580 --> 00:02:39,590
don't want to have
visible seams.

40
00:02:39,590 --> 00:02:41,350
You have to be
bent at the edges,

41
00:02:41,350 --> 00:02:44,570
so it's not such a big
deal if you're also

42
00:02:44,570 --> 00:02:46,467
fusing along an edge.

43
00:02:46,467 --> 00:02:48,550
But in general, you could
imagine cutting anywhere

44
00:02:48,550 --> 00:02:50,840
on the surface, and
this is an example

45
00:02:50,840 --> 00:02:52,560
where the solid red
lines are cutting

46
00:02:52,560 --> 00:02:54,500
on what you see and the
dotted red lines were

47
00:02:54,500 --> 00:02:57,010
cutting on the backside.

48
00:02:57,010 --> 00:03:01,650
And when you unfold that thing,
you get this stoplight polygon,

49
00:03:01,650 --> 00:03:05,120
and this is what we call a
general unfolding, or just

50
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:07,790
unfolding.

51
00:03:07,790 --> 00:03:09,510
There you can cut anywhere.

52
00:03:09,510 --> 00:03:16,310
In both cases, we want
one piece, no overlap,

53
00:03:16,310 --> 00:03:19,240
but you can change where
you're allowed to cut.

54
00:03:19,240 --> 00:03:39,730

55
00:03:39,730 --> 00:03:41,620
So those are the
rules of the game,

56
00:03:41,620 --> 00:03:45,080
or two possible
rules of the game.

57
00:03:45,080 --> 00:03:49,850
And let me tell you what's
known about these kinds

58
00:03:49,850 --> 00:03:51,430
of unfoldings.

59
00:03:51,430 --> 00:03:53,560
I've mentioned it way
back in lecture one.

60
00:03:53,560 --> 00:04:26,329

61
00:04:26,329 --> 00:04:27,870
so we can think
about edge unfolding,

62
00:04:27,870 --> 00:04:29,411
we can think about
general unfolding,

63
00:04:29,411 --> 00:04:31,840
and we can think about
them for convex polyhedra--

64
00:04:31,840 --> 00:04:35,080
simple things like the
cube have no dents--

65
00:04:35,080 --> 00:04:39,850
or general polyhedra,
non-convex polyhedra.

66
00:04:39,850 --> 00:04:45,260
And status is these
two corners are open.

67
00:04:45,260 --> 00:04:49,360

68
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:52,155
This one is solved.

69
00:04:52,155 --> 00:04:53,460
It can always be done.

70
00:04:53,460 --> 00:04:56,800
You can always generally
unfold a convex polyhedron,

71
00:04:56,800 --> 00:05:00,580
but we don't know about
general polyhedra.

72
00:05:00,580 --> 00:05:02,310
Edge unfolding of
convex polyhedra,

73
00:05:02,310 --> 00:05:04,819
we don't know whether
it's possible,

74
00:05:04,819 --> 00:05:06,360
but for non-convex
polyhedra, we know

75
00:05:06,360 --> 00:05:07,944
that's too much to hope for.

76
00:05:07,944 --> 00:05:10,670

77
00:05:10,670 --> 00:05:13,890
Not always possible.

78
00:05:13,890 --> 00:05:17,900
Both of these questions
could go either way,

79
00:05:17,900 --> 00:05:21,820
but we know in various
generalizations, easy case

80
00:05:21,820 --> 00:05:25,950
of convex polyhedra general
unfolding, we can do it.

81
00:05:25,950 --> 00:05:27,760
The most restrictive,
hardest situation

82
00:05:27,760 --> 00:05:29,970
is edge unfolding
non-convex polyhedra.

83
00:05:29,970 --> 00:05:31,180
That's too much.

84
00:05:31,180 --> 00:05:33,481
But each of these
things, we don't know.

85
00:05:33,481 --> 00:05:35,480
And these are some of the
biggest open questions

86
00:05:35,480 --> 00:05:40,830
remaining in geometric folding
algorithms, this field.

87
00:05:40,830 --> 00:05:46,970
I'm going to talk mostly
about these three things

88
00:05:46,970 --> 00:05:52,080
today, so this open problem
and these two results.

89
00:05:52,080 --> 00:05:56,420
And then this topic will
essentially be next lecture.

90
00:05:56,420 --> 00:05:59,665
Obviously it's not solved, but
we still have a lot to say.

91
00:05:59,665 --> 00:06:01,040
There are various
partial results

92
00:06:01,040 --> 00:06:05,140
toward solving both
of those problems,

93
00:06:05,140 --> 00:06:08,090
I would say more on this one.

94
00:06:08,090 --> 00:06:10,280
This one is five centuries old.

95
00:06:10,280 --> 00:06:14,258
This one is one
decade old or so.

96
00:06:14,258 --> 00:06:25,551

97
00:06:25,551 --> 00:06:27,550
So I need to set the stage
a little bit before I

98
00:06:27,550 --> 00:06:29,900
can talk about any
of these things,

99
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:33,180
so let me start with a
little bit of terminology.

100
00:06:33,180 --> 00:06:39,720

101
00:06:39,720 --> 00:06:42,560
We've in some sense talked
about curvature before.

102
00:06:42,560 --> 00:06:44,310
I don't think I gave
it this name, though,

103
00:06:44,310 --> 00:06:45,393
in the context of origami.

104
00:06:45,393 --> 00:06:50,360

105
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:52,490
And I use it almost
subconsciously

106
00:06:52,490 --> 00:06:54,060
so it's good for
me to define it.

107
00:06:54,060 --> 00:07:00,310

108
00:07:00,310 --> 00:07:03,240
If you have some vertex
on your polyhedron.

109
00:07:03,240 --> 00:07:06,570
Let's say we're looking
at a corner of a cube,

110
00:07:06,570 --> 00:07:12,160
so this has three 90 degree
angles coming together.

111
00:07:12,160 --> 00:07:16,700
You sum those
angles, we get 270,

112
00:07:16,700 --> 00:07:19,610
and then you take
360 minus that sum,

113
00:07:19,610 --> 00:07:22,375
and that is your curvature.

114
00:07:22,375 --> 00:07:25,680
This is going to be 90.

115
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:28,050
And what I really care about
is whether the curvature

116
00:07:28,050 --> 00:07:31,090
is positive, 0, or negative.

117
00:07:31,090 --> 00:07:38,792

118
00:07:38,792 --> 00:07:40,750
Positive curvature, which
is what we got here--

119
00:07:40,750 --> 00:07:44,220
this is plus 90-- is
like a convex cone.

120
00:07:44,220 --> 00:07:51,470

121
00:07:51,470 --> 00:07:53,860
So if you're thinking about
convex polyhedra, which

122
00:07:53,860 --> 00:07:55,870
is one of the situations
we care about,

123
00:07:55,870 --> 00:08:01,680
you'll always get positive or
0, maybe, curvature vertices,

124
00:08:01,680 --> 00:08:03,620
depending on what
you're thinking about.

125
00:08:03,620 --> 00:08:05,750
Zero, this is like
a piece of paper,

126
00:08:05,750 --> 00:08:10,180
so this is what you might call
flat, but it's locally flat.

127
00:08:10,180 --> 00:08:13,700
It could be drawn
flat or we know

128
00:08:13,700 --> 00:08:16,290
how to fold pieces of paper.

129
00:08:16,290 --> 00:08:17,880
You never change the curvature.

130
00:08:17,880 --> 00:08:18,700
The sum of the
instant face angles

131
00:08:18,700 --> 00:08:21,230
will always stay the same, no
matter how you fold this thing.

132
00:08:21,230 --> 00:08:22,313
Curvature is an invariant.

133
00:08:22,313 --> 00:08:25,280

134
00:08:25,280 --> 00:08:28,520
If you just think locally and
forget about the actual folding

135
00:08:28,520 --> 00:08:31,669
of the thing, it's kind of flat.

136
00:08:31,669 --> 00:08:33,860
So you can think of this
as a piece of paper.

137
00:08:33,860 --> 00:08:35,460
We talked about
these two situations

138
00:08:35,460 --> 00:08:38,211
in the context of Kawasaki's
theorem way back when.

139
00:08:38,211 --> 00:08:39,669
Kawasaki's theorem
applied for both

140
00:08:39,669 --> 00:08:42,030
of these for the negative
curvature case, which

141
00:08:42,030 --> 00:08:44,720
is when you have lots
of material all joined

142
00:08:44,720 --> 00:08:48,040
at a single point,
something like this.

143
00:08:48,040 --> 00:08:52,800

144
00:08:52,800 --> 00:08:58,200
Then Kawasaki's theorem
changed a little bit.

145
00:08:58,200 --> 00:09:00,894
There were some other
cases that could happen.

146
00:09:00,894 --> 00:09:02,310
So when you have
tons of material,

147
00:09:02,310 --> 00:09:05,269
this can only happen in
a non-convex polyhedron.

148
00:09:05,269 --> 00:09:06,310
That's sort of the point.

149
00:09:06,310 --> 00:09:07,895
If you're a convex
polyhedron, you

150
00:09:07,895 --> 00:09:10,870
know you have to have
only these two situations.

151
00:09:10,870 --> 00:09:12,260
Where do you get flat vertices?

152
00:09:12,260 --> 00:09:14,990
Well, if you think of
this point as a vertex

153
00:09:14,990 --> 00:09:18,380
and you add up all the angles
around it, well, that's 360.

154
00:09:18,380 --> 00:09:20,720
360 minus 360 is 0.

155
00:09:20,720 --> 00:09:24,100
So you have zero curvature on
all the faces and on the edges.

156
00:09:24,100 --> 00:09:27,830
Also, if you look here,
you have 180 and other 180.

157
00:09:27,830 --> 00:09:30,040
That adds to 360.

158
00:09:30,040 --> 00:09:32,030
And then at the actual
vertices, that's

159
00:09:32,030 --> 00:09:35,840
where you have positive
curvature for a convex

160
00:09:35,840 --> 00:09:37,320
polyhedron.

161
00:09:37,320 --> 00:09:38,840
So just some terminology.

162
00:09:38,840 --> 00:09:41,340
Get used to the idea of positive
curvature, zero curvature,

163
00:09:41,340 --> 00:09:42,298
and negative curvature.

164
00:09:42,298 --> 00:09:45,730

165
00:09:45,730 --> 00:09:50,180
Then we have the
idea of a cutting.

166
00:09:50,180 --> 00:09:52,900
So cutting is just,
what edges do you cut?

167
00:09:52,900 --> 00:09:55,240
It's the red stuff
in this picture.

168
00:09:55,240 --> 00:09:57,360
What edges do you cut
in order to unfold?

169
00:09:57,360 --> 00:10:02,230
So this is an unfolding, the
mapping here, but the red part,

170
00:10:02,230 --> 00:10:03,269
I'll call it cutting.

171
00:10:03,269 --> 00:10:04,935
Sometimes it's also
called an unfolding,

172
00:10:04,935 --> 00:10:06,393
but that can be a
little confusing.

173
00:10:06,393 --> 00:10:17,440

174
00:10:17,440 --> 00:10:20,630
The main point here is I want
to talk about what constraints

175
00:10:20,630 --> 00:10:23,650
cutting must satisfy in order
to be valid so we can just

176
00:10:23,650 --> 00:10:27,380
get a sense of what
is happening here.

177
00:10:27,380 --> 00:10:34,430
If you look at these pictures,
you can see two properties.

178
00:10:34,430 --> 00:10:37,820
One is that the cuttings
visit all the vertices

179
00:10:37,820 --> 00:10:40,390
of the polyhedron.

180
00:10:40,390 --> 00:10:42,110
So there's this red stuff.

181
00:10:42,110 --> 00:10:45,240
The red stuff is connected.

182
00:10:45,240 --> 00:10:48,850
It's acyclic, so it's actually
a tree in these pictures,

183
00:10:48,850 --> 00:10:51,380
and it's visiting
all the corners.

184
00:10:51,380 --> 00:10:54,830
Even back here, it's
visited on the back.

185
00:10:54,830 --> 00:10:56,050
Is that always true?

186
00:10:56,050 --> 00:10:59,160
Most of those properties
are mostly true,

187
00:10:59,160 --> 00:11:01,650
but it depends a little bit.

188
00:11:01,650 --> 00:11:05,080
One thing that is
sure is the cutting

189
00:11:05,080 --> 00:11:11,515
must span all non-zero
curvature vertices.

190
00:11:11,515 --> 00:11:15,130

191
00:11:15,130 --> 00:11:21,560
But I do have to say
"non-zero curvature." "Spans"

192
00:11:21,560 --> 00:11:23,560
just means visits.

193
00:11:23,560 --> 00:11:26,830
You have to hit all the
vertices of non-zero curvature

194
00:11:26,830 --> 00:11:29,050
because anything of
non-zero curvature

195
00:11:29,050 --> 00:11:30,860
can't be flattened by itself.

196
00:11:30,860 --> 00:11:31,750
It needs to be cut.

197
00:11:31,750 --> 00:11:35,090

198
00:11:35,090 --> 00:11:38,140
At that point, the cutting has
to have degree at least one.

199
00:11:38,140 --> 00:11:41,290

200
00:11:41,290 --> 00:11:43,590
With zero curvature
vertices, even if they're not

201
00:11:43,590 --> 00:11:46,995
flat in three dimensions,
you could flatten them

202
00:11:46,995 --> 00:11:49,120
because we know locally,
it really is a flat thing.

203
00:11:49,120 --> 00:11:51,484
So there may not be any cuts
at zero curvature vertices.

204
00:11:51,484 --> 00:11:53,650
Most of the time, we won't
have to worry about them,

205
00:11:53,650 --> 00:11:56,200
but something to think about.

206
00:11:56,200 --> 00:11:57,940
Everybody else you have to span.

207
00:11:57,940 --> 00:12:03,470

208
00:12:03,470 --> 00:12:05,520
You can say even more.

209
00:12:05,520 --> 00:12:09,180
If you have very
negative curvature,

210
00:12:09,180 --> 00:12:11,760
if the curvature of a vertex
is less than some integer,

211
00:12:11,760 --> 00:12:23,520
k times 360 with a minus
sign in front, then cutting

212
00:12:23,520 --> 00:12:32,260
must have degree strictly
more than k plus 1.

213
00:12:32,260 --> 00:12:34,180
So if you have
negative curvature,

214
00:12:34,180 --> 00:12:38,764
you know you have to
have at least two cuts

215
00:12:38,764 --> 00:12:40,680
for a negative curvature
vertex because if you

216
00:12:40,680 --> 00:12:43,770
had negative curvature--
one of these things--

217
00:12:43,770 --> 00:12:44,880
you made a single cut.

218
00:12:44,880 --> 00:12:46,570
Then all that material
is still there.

219
00:12:46,570 --> 00:12:48,990
If you then flattened it,
it's going to overlap itself

220
00:12:48,990 --> 00:12:50,865
because you're trying
to flatten it into 360.

221
00:12:50,865 --> 00:12:53,580
There's more than
360 material there.

222
00:12:53,580 --> 00:12:57,090
So negative curvature already,
you need two vertices.

223
00:12:57,090 --> 00:12:59,630
That's the plus 1 here.

224
00:12:59,630 --> 00:13:06,110
And as soon as you get to
smaller than negative 360,

225
00:13:06,110 --> 00:13:08,860
then you have to have at least
three cuts and so on, just

226
00:13:08,860 --> 00:13:11,425
to partition up into
at most 360 groups.

227
00:13:11,425 --> 00:13:14,200

228
00:13:14,200 --> 00:13:15,420
This is useful.

229
00:13:15,420 --> 00:13:17,670
Negative curvature is basically
really tough to unfold

230
00:13:17,670 --> 00:13:21,820
and we'll use that to make
counter examples here.

231
00:13:21,820 --> 00:13:22,390
What else?

232
00:13:22,390 --> 00:13:35,440

233
00:13:35,440 --> 00:13:47,665
your polyhedron has no handles,
then cutting has no cycles.

234
00:13:47,665 --> 00:13:56,120

235
00:13:56,120 --> 00:13:59,900
A handle is something
of higher genus.

236
00:13:59,900 --> 00:14:03,616
If this is your polyhedron,
we call this a handle.

237
00:14:03,616 --> 00:14:04,990
You have sort of
a blob down here

238
00:14:04,990 --> 00:14:08,230
and you have a connection
from one place to the other.

239
00:14:08,230 --> 00:14:10,100
If you have a
handle, you can have

240
00:14:10,100 --> 00:14:13,280
a cycle of cuts like this
that does not disconnect

241
00:14:13,280 --> 00:14:16,050
the surface, but we
basically never think

242
00:14:16,050 --> 00:14:17,855
about that situation.

243
00:14:17,855 --> 00:14:19,980
Whenever we're thinking of
something of genus zero,

244
00:14:19,980 --> 00:14:25,239
like a convex polyhedron or a
regular, non-convex polyhedron,

245
00:14:25,239 --> 00:14:27,280
you really shouldn't have
a cycle in your cutting

246
00:14:27,280 --> 00:14:28,750
because if you
had a cycle, you'd

247
00:14:28,750 --> 00:14:31,420
disconnect your
surface into two parts

248
00:14:31,420 --> 00:14:33,900
normally, if you're like
a sphere or like a disk.

249
00:14:33,900 --> 00:14:36,730

250
00:14:36,730 --> 00:14:40,410
That's the acyclic
condition and when it holds.

251
00:14:40,410 --> 00:14:41,560
Some other good things.

252
00:14:41,560 --> 00:14:56,730

253
00:14:56,730 --> 00:15:08,060
If a polyhedron has no
boundary and no handles,

254
00:15:08,060 --> 00:15:24,780
and the unfolding has
no holes, then cutting

255
00:15:24,780 --> 00:15:28,210
is a spanning tree.

256
00:15:28,210 --> 00:15:30,730

257
00:15:30,730 --> 00:15:34,030
Spanning tree, it's a concept
we've used a few times.

