of this working,

1014
00:52:52,930 --> 00:52:56,180
that structure better be useful,
but I don't know how to use it.

1015
00:52:56,180 --> 00:52:58,140
But in particular,
open question.

1016
00:52:58,140 --> 00:53:00,930
If I give you a super
shallow, arbitrarily

1017
00:53:00,930 --> 00:53:06,040
shallow, convex polyhedral
dome, can it be unfolded?

1018
00:53:06,040 --> 00:53:06,770
I don't know.

1019
00:53:06,770 --> 00:53:10,790

1020
00:53:10,790 --> 00:53:13,170
Maybe we'll work on it
in the problem session.

1021
00:53:13,170 --> 00:53:15,926

1022
00:53:15,926 --> 00:53:17,425
Haven't thought
about it for awhile.

1023
00:53:17,425 --> 00:53:20,390

1024
00:53:20,390 --> 00:53:23,340
That's if you want
to solve everything.

1025
00:53:23,340 --> 00:53:27,080
What if you just want to
solve some special cases?

1026
00:53:27,080 --> 00:53:31,400
That is a special case
motivated by the general case.

1027
00:53:31,400 --> 00:53:34,420
Well, you can solve the
case of a polyhedron

1028
00:53:34,420 --> 00:53:35,630
with at most six vertices.

1029
00:53:35,630 --> 00:53:38,450
That's as far as we've gotten.

1030
00:53:38,450 --> 00:53:41,710
You can solve some simple
examples like pyramids

1031
00:53:41,710 --> 00:53:45,880
if you take any convex
polygon, doesn't

1032
00:53:45,880 --> 00:53:47,409
have to be irregular
or anything,

1033
00:53:47,409 --> 00:53:49,700
and then you take a point
and you take the convex hull.

1034
00:53:49,700 --> 00:53:52,280

1035
00:53:52,280 --> 00:53:54,860
So that's a polyhedron
and it unfolds.

1036
00:53:54,860 --> 00:53:56,080
How does it unfold?

1037
00:53:56,080 --> 00:53:57,350
Any suggestions where to cut?

1038
00:53:57,350 --> 00:54:03,170

1039
00:54:03,170 --> 00:54:05,454
How?

1040
00:54:05,454 --> 00:54:06,930
AUDIENCE: From the top?

1041
00:54:06,930 --> 00:54:08,370
PROFESSOR: From the top.

1042
00:54:08,370 --> 00:54:10,000
Yeah, just cut here.

1043
00:54:10,000 --> 00:54:12,180
Here, we're only allowed
to cut along edges.

1044
00:54:12,180 --> 00:54:16,521
This is called the
volcano unfolding.

1045
00:54:16,521 --> 00:54:17,510
What do we have?

1046
00:54:17,510 --> 00:54:22,810
Like that, and then there's
just a bunch of triangles.

1047
00:54:22,810 --> 00:54:24,840
What's nice about
the volcano unfolding

1048
00:54:24,840 --> 00:54:30,870
is if you look at these
perpendicular strips here,

1049
00:54:30,870 --> 00:54:34,100
those triangles will fit inside
those perpendicular strips,

1050
00:54:34,100 --> 00:54:36,870
and therefore they won't
intersect each other

1051
00:54:36,870 --> 00:54:38,870
because these strips don't
intersect each other.

1052
00:54:38,870 --> 00:54:40,620
You could probably
even continuously bloom

1053
00:54:40,620 --> 00:54:41,440
this, no problem.

1054
00:54:41,440 --> 00:54:45,497
So a very simple example,
easy to do with volcanoes.

1055
00:54:45,497 --> 00:54:46,705
That's the so-called pyramid.

1056
00:54:46,705 --> 00:54:50,530

1057
00:54:50,530 --> 00:54:55,740
Prism, a little bit more
interesting, but not by much.

1058
00:54:55,740 --> 00:54:59,291
You take some polygon.

1059
00:54:59,291 --> 00:55:01,510
Again, doesn't
have to be regular,

1060
00:55:01,510 --> 00:55:04,804
but you take two copies of
it vertically offset, take

1061
00:55:04,804 --> 00:55:05,470
the convex hull.

1062
00:55:05,470 --> 00:55:08,100

1063
00:55:08,100 --> 00:55:14,010
This one you can
cut in two ways.

1064
00:55:14,010 --> 00:55:15,420
You could do a
volcano-like thing

1065
00:55:15,420 --> 00:55:19,850
where you cut all
the vertical edges

1066
00:55:19,850 --> 00:55:24,360
and then you cut all but
one of the bottom edges.

1067
00:55:24,360 --> 00:55:29,780
Then you'll have basically a
volcano with little rectangles

1068
00:55:29,780 --> 00:55:32,920
hanging off all the sides.

1069
00:55:32,920 --> 00:55:37,154
And then there's another copy,
the bottom copy of this face,

1070
00:55:37,154 --> 00:55:38,820
and it just hangs out
over here, and you

1071
00:55:38,820 --> 00:55:40,590
could prove that that
won't hit anybody

1072
00:55:40,590 --> 00:55:42,750
in this very simple situation.

1073
00:55:42,750 --> 00:55:45,760
There's another unfolding,
though, that I mention

1074
00:55:45,760 --> 00:55:49,580
because it's useful
for other things,

1075
00:55:49,580 --> 00:55:51,405
and it's so-called
band unfolding.

1076
00:55:51,405 --> 00:55:57,720
Band unfolding, I
want to keep intact

1077
00:55:57,720 --> 00:56:03,766
the radial band around the
thing, maybe like this.

1078
00:56:03,766 --> 00:56:07,100
What do I want to do
to keep that edge?

1079
00:56:07,100 --> 00:56:08,950
Cut, cut.

1080
00:56:08,950 --> 00:56:11,100
So I cut on all the
top edges except one,

1081
00:56:11,100 --> 00:56:13,200
I cut on all the bottom
edges except the same one,

1082
00:56:13,200 --> 00:56:16,610
and then I also cut
this vertical edge.

1083
00:56:16,610 --> 00:56:21,060
So what I should get
is I get my top face,

1084
00:56:21,060 --> 00:56:23,520
then I get a
rectangle, then I get

1085
00:56:23,520 --> 00:56:26,520
the band that goes
around the outside,

1086
00:56:26,520 --> 00:56:31,986
and then I get another copy
of my shape, the bottom side.

1087
00:56:31,986 --> 00:56:33,485
This is what we
call band unfolding.

1088
00:56:33,485 --> 00:56:36,390

1089
00:56:36,390 --> 00:56:39,600
There's some nice theorems about
band unfoldings working out.

1090
00:56:39,600 --> 00:56:43,940

1091
00:56:43,940 --> 00:56:46,190
Let me get to more
interesting polyhedra.

1092
00:56:46,190 --> 00:56:49,280

1093
00:56:49,280 --> 00:56:51,150
These are some
pretty simple cases,

1094
00:56:51,150 --> 00:56:54,680
but we don't know very
much on the positive side.

1095
00:56:54,680 --> 00:57:04,731

1096
00:57:04,731 --> 00:57:05,230
Prismoid.

1097
00:57:05,230 --> 00:57:12,500

1098
00:57:12,500 --> 00:57:19,980
Suppose you take a polygon,
and you basically inset it.

1099
00:57:19,980 --> 00:57:23,900
So I want to make a new
version of the polygon

1100
00:57:23,900 --> 00:57:31,600
where all of the angles match,
so these edges are parallel

1101
00:57:31,600 --> 00:57:32,260
to each other.

1102
00:57:32,260 --> 00:57:35,670
I think, actually, the
lengths can change.

1103
00:57:35,670 --> 00:57:37,435
And then you take
the convex hull.

1104
00:57:37,435 --> 00:57:40,290

1105
00:57:40,290 --> 00:57:42,665
These unfold with the
volcano unfolding.

1106
00:57:42,665 --> 00:57:45,524

1107
00:57:45,524 --> 00:57:46,940
It's a little more
subtle to prove

1108
00:57:46,940 --> 00:57:49,680
but it's proved in the textbook.

1109
00:57:49,680 --> 00:57:54,220

1110
00:57:54,220 --> 00:57:56,570
Edges have to stay parallel.

1111
00:57:56,570 --> 00:57:59,076
I think that might
force something.

1112
00:57:59,076 --> 00:58:00,700
I'm not quite sure,
but the constraints

1113
00:58:00,700 --> 00:58:01,800
are that the edges
have to be parallel

1114
00:58:01,800 --> 00:58:03,133
and the angles have to be equal.

1115
00:58:03,133 --> 00:58:07,870

1116
00:58:07,870 --> 00:58:09,160
Dome.

1117
00:58:09,160 --> 00:58:12,660
Dome is actually in
some ways simpler.

1118
00:58:12,660 --> 00:58:20,220
You take some base, and then
I want a whole bunch of faces

1119
00:58:20,220 --> 00:58:22,000
that all touch the base.

1120
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:26,110
So in general, it's going to be
like a tree of faces, something

1121
00:58:26,110 --> 00:58:28,210
like this.

1122
00:58:28,210 --> 00:58:31,340
Every face has to touch
an edge of the base.

1123
00:58:31,340 --> 00:58:33,905
These also unfold, and
also with a volcano.

1124
00:58:33,905 --> 00:58:36,560

1125
00:58:36,560 --> 00:58:39,990
This is proved also
in the textbook.

1126
00:58:39,990 --> 00:58:41,956
Both results are
by Joe O'Rourke.

1127
00:58:41,956 --> 00:58:45,150

1128
00:58:45,150 --> 00:58:46,880
Prismatoid.

1129
00:58:46,880 --> 00:58:49,370
This is the coolest
special case I'm

1130
00:58:49,370 --> 00:58:52,880
going to talk about,
the most interesting.

1131
00:58:52,880 --> 00:58:58,840
I take some convex polygon,
and then in a parallel offset,

1132
00:58:58,840 --> 00:59:05,837
I take some other
convex polygon--

1133
00:59:05,837 --> 00:59:07,712
no relation to each
other except that they're

1134
00:59:07,712 --> 00:59:09,450
in parallel planes--
and then I take

1135
00:59:09,450 --> 00:59:15,140
the convex hull,
something like that.

1136
00:59:15,140 --> 00:59:21,660

1137
00:59:21,660 --> 00:59:23,095
This one, sadly, is open.

1138
00:59:23,095 --> 00:59:26,750

1139
00:59:26,750 --> 00:59:28,610
Now, what we do know,
and this is related

1140
00:59:28,610 --> 00:59:32,160
to the band
unfolding, if you look

1141
00:59:32,160 --> 00:59:38,150
at the band around the
sides of this prismatoid

1142
00:59:38,150 --> 00:59:40,960
and just unfold
that by itself, that

1143
00:59:40,960 --> 00:59:44,660
will not self intersect,
and that's quite nontrivial,

1144
00:59:44,660 --> 00:59:45,320
the proof.

1145
00:59:45,320 --> 00:59:48,540
But if you just
unroll the side faces,

1146
00:59:48,540 --> 00:59:52,541
they will wander around but
they won't hit themselves.

1147
00:59:52,541 --> 00:59:54,040
The only remaining
problem is, where

1148
00:59:54,040 --> 00:59:57,460
does the top and
the bottom face go?

1149
00:59:57,460 --> 01:00:01,420
I think I have an example
where that's a little dicey.

1150
01:00:01,420 --> 01:00:03,560
Prism.

1151
01:00:03,560 --> 01:00:04,360
Prismoid.

1152
01:00:04,360 --> 01:00:06,620
That gives you an
answer to your offset.

1153
01:00:06,620 --> 01:00:09,570
So they can be sheared
away from each other,

1154
01:00:09,570 --> 01:00:12,340
but this is a prismoid.

1155
01:00:12,340 --> 01:00:16,920
All of the sides are parallel
and the angles match, a and b.

1156
01:00:16,920 --> 01:00:22,400
Here is the volcano
unfolding of the prismoid,

1157
01:00:22,400 --> 01:00:26,080
and here's showing that it's
not so obvious that it always

1158
01:00:26,080 --> 01:00:26,580
works.

1159
01:00:26,580 --> 01:00:29,830
If you're not careful where
you put the top face-- so this

1160
01:00:29,830 --> 01:00:33,730
is a on top of b
in plan-- you could

1161
01:00:33,730 --> 01:00:36,360
attach a to any of these faces.

1162
01:00:36,360 --> 01:00:37,750
You have to choose
one that's not

1163
01:00:37,750 --> 01:00:40,920
so inside because
it's overlapping here.

1164
01:00:40,920 --> 01:00:42,420
But if you choose
the outermost one,

1165
01:00:42,420 --> 01:00:45,390
it works and you can prove that.

1166
01:00:45,390 --> 01:00:50,990
This is the dome.

1167
01:00:50,990 --> 01:00:53,400
You can even have
overhang and they

1168
01:00:53,400 --> 01:00:56,690
will unfold, volcano style.

1169
01:00:56,690 --> 01:00:59,760
You no longer have those
nice perpendicular wedges

1170
01:00:59,760 --> 01:01:01,150
to say everything is disjoined.

1171
01:01:01,150 --> 01:01:02,219
But it still turns out.

1172
01:01:02,219 --> 01:01:03,010
Nothing intersects.

1173
01:01:03,010 --> 01:01:05,880

1174
01:01:05,880 --> 01:01:08,790
Here's the prismatoid
I wanted to show you.

1175
01:01:08,790 --> 01:01:11,320
This one's actually almost flat.

1176
01:01:11,320 --> 01:01:15,790
So a is this triangle right on
top of b, the triangle beneath.

1177
01:01:15,790 --> 01:01:17,290
You take the convex
hull and you get

1178
01:01:17,290 --> 01:01:20,470
all those edges on the outside.

1179
01:01:20,470 --> 01:01:23,210
And if you're not careful--
this is more volcano

1180
01:01:23,210 --> 01:01:26,245
style unfolding-- but
you can get overlap.

1181
01:01:26,245 --> 01:01:31,520

1182
01:01:31,520 --> 01:01:36,410
One thing we do know,
this is kind of weird.

1183
01:01:36,410 --> 01:01:40,880
If you try to go more general,
and instead of taking a convex

1184
01:01:40,880 --> 01:01:43,470
polygon on the top and a
convex polygon on the bottom,

1185
01:01:43,470 --> 01:01:45,790
instead you take a
smooth convex curve

1186
01:01:45,790 --> 01:01:47,390
on the top and a
smooth convex curve

1187
01:01:47,390 --> 01:01:50,094
on the bottom, which is getting
weird because now there's

1188
01:01:50,094 --> 01:01:51,510
infinitely many
vertices and going

1189
01:01:51,510 --> 01:01:53,700
to be infinitely many cuts.

1190
01:01:53,700 --> 01:01:57,940
But there is a natural
notion of unfolding

1191
01:01:57,940 --> 01:01:59,490
which sort of takes
the continuum.

1192
01:01:59,490 --> 01:02:02,315
You take all those lines
that go from one side

1193
01:02:02,315 --> 01:02:07,130
to the other, the rule
lines of the convex shape,

1194
01:02:07,130 --> 01:02:09,147
and you just unfold them.

1195
01:02:09,147 --> 01:02:11,230
You don't actually preserve
area when you do this.

1196
01:02:11,230 --> 01:02:14,080
It's not a valid unfolding
in the usual sense,

1197
01:02:14,080 --> 01:02:15,930
but it's a natural
generalization

1198
01:02:15,930 --> 01:02:18,256
of unfolding to smooth shapes.

1199
01:02:18,256 --> 01:02:20,880
You can prove, well, that part's
going to work just fine if you

1200
01:02:20,880 --> 01:02:22,910
just volcano it, and
then you can actually

1201
01:02:22,910 --> 01:02:25,920
find a place for the top face.

1202
01:02:25,920 --> 01:02:33,420

1203
01:02:33,420 --> 01:02:34,920
Those are the special
cases we know,

1204
01:02:34,920 --> 01:02:37,280
and even some pretty simple
cases that we don't know,

1205
01:02:37,280 --> 01:02:39,980
although it's almost there.

1206
01:02:39,980 --> 01:02:54,859

1207
01:02:54,859 --> 01:02:55,775
One more open problem.

1208
01:02:55,775 --> 01:03:21,216

1209
01:03:21,216 --> 01:03:23,090
Just mention this because
it's a fun problem.

1210
01:03:23,090 --> 01:03:25,930

1211
01:03:25,930 --> 01:03:37,880
So again, I want to edge
unfold all convex polyhedra,

1212
01:03:37,880 --> 01:03:41,209
but I allow multiple
pieces to make

1213
01:03:41,209 --> 01:03:42,375
the problem a little easier.

1214
01:03:42,375 --> 01:03:45,640

1215
01:03:45,640 --> 01:03:53,190
So let's say I have a
polyhedron with f faces.

1216
01:03:53,190 --> 01:03:56,240
I want to know how few
pieces could I get away with?

1217
01:03:56,240 --> 01:03:59,336
The big open problem is, can
I get away with one piece?

1218
01:03:59,336 --> 01:04:00,460
What if you make it easier?

1219
01:04:00,460 --> 01:04:05,260
What if I just want, say,
little o of f pieces?

1220
01:04:05,260 --> 01:04:07,910
Smaller than any
constant times f.

1221
01:04:07,910 --> 01:04:08,790
This is open.

1222
01:04:08,790 --> 01:04:12,710

1223
01:04:12,710 --> 01:04:14,890
What we do know is
some constant times

1224
01:04:14,890 --> 01:04:19,210
f where the constant
is less than 1.

1225
01:04:19,210 --> 01:04:22,730
Best constant I have
written here is 1/2.

1226
01:04:22,730 --> 01:04:24,400
There is a better
bound, but I think

1227
01:04:24,400 --> 01:04:27,057
it's not so easy to
summarize in this form.

1228
01:04:27,057 --> 01:04:28,640
So you can get a
little less than half

1229
01:04:28,640 --> 01:04:31,880
the faces' number of pieces,
but that's pretty pathetic.

1230
01:04:31,880 --> 01:04:35,007

1231
01:04:35,007 --> 01:04:37,340
It's a problem that seemed
like it would be a good idea,

1232
01:04:37,340 --> 01:04:39,950
but so far it hasn't seemed to
make the problem much easier.

1233
01:04:39,950 --> 01:04:44,170

1234
01:04:44,170 --> 01:04:46,310
What do I mean by pieces?

1235
01:04:46,310 --> 01:04:49,080
Well, we're all about
one piece unfolding,

1236
01:04:49,080 --> 01:04:52,670
so now your cutting
can have cycles in it

1237
01:04:52,670 --> 01:04:54,815
and disconnect the surface
into multiple parts.

1238
01:04:54,815 --> 01:04:55,731
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

1239
01:04:55,731 --> 01:04:58,252

1240
01:04:58,252 --> 01:04:59,960
PROFESSOR: Multiple
connected components.

1241
01:04:59,960 --> 01:05:14,926

1242
01:05:14,926 --> 01:05:16,550
The tricky part is
to pair up the faces

1243
01:05:16,550 --> 01:05:19,550
so that everybody has a mate.

1244
01:05:19,550 --> 01:05:22,010
That's not always possible.

1245
01:05:22,010 --> 01:05:23,634
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

1246
01:05:23,634 --> 01:05:24,300
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

1247
01:05:24,300 --> 01:05:28,380
You would hope that one
third, but-- I mean,

1248
01:05:28,380 --> 01:05:30,200
you can do lots of
little local arguments

1249
01:05:30,200 --> 01:05:33,299
and prove this constant,
but the big question

1250
01:05:33,299 --> 01:05:34,840
is, can you get less
than a constant?

1251
01:05:34,840 --> 01:05:44,230

1252
01:05:44,230 --> 01:05:50,115
So last topic for today is edge
unfolding non-convex polyhedra.

1253
01:05:50,115 --> 01:05:56,470

1254
01:05:56,470 --> 01:05:59,710
Sort of did that
problem addressed,

1255
01:05:59,710 --> 01:06:02,830
and now this is not
always possible.

1256
01:06:02,830 --> 01:06:05,700
So I want to give you a
polyhedron where you cannot

1257
01:06:05,700 --> 01:06:06,410
edge unfold it.

1258
01:06:06,410 --> 01:06:10,010
This is actually pretty easy,
and we did it way back in '98

1259
01:06:10,010 --> 01:06:11,840
when we started
working on folding,

1260
01:06:11,840 --> 01:06:14,310
but it's kind of cheating.

1261
01:06:14,310 --> 01:06:18,130
This is a box on a box,
and the only edges here

1262
01:06:18,130 --> 01:06:20,290
are the edges of the two boxes.

1263
01:06:20,290 --> 01:06:22,960
There's no edges connecting
the outside of this face

1264
01:06:22,960 --> 01:06:24,170
to the inside of that face.

1265
01:06:24,170 --> 01:06:28,430
That face here is a donut.

1266
01:06:28,430 --> 01:06:29,340
It's a square donut.

1267
01:06:29,340 --> 01:06:32,580

1268
01:06:32,580 --> 01:06:37,090
So if you're only cutting along
